{
  "Which of the following is the Pythagorean identity?": "",
  "sin²x + cos²x = 0": "",
  "sin x + cos x = 1": "",
  "sin²x - cos²x = 1": "",
  "sin²x + cos²x = 1": "",
  "The fundamental Pythagorean identity states that sin²x + cos²x = 1 for all values of x. This is derived from the Pythagorean theorem applied to the unit circle.": "",
  "Simplify: tan x · cos x.": "",
  "sec x": "",
  "sin x": "",
  "cos x": "",
  "1": "",
  "Since tan x = sin x / cos x, multiplying by cos x gives (sin x / cos x)(cos x) = sin x.": "",
  "What is the double-angle formula for sin 2x?": "",
  "sin²x - cos²x": "",
  "cos²x - sin²x": "",
  "2 sin²x": "",
  "2 sin x cos x": "",
  "The double-angle formula for sine is sin 2x = 2 sin x cos x. This can be derived from the angle addition formula sin(a + b) with a = b = x.": "",
  "If sin x = 3/5 and x is in Quadrant I, what is cos x?": "",
  "4/5": "",
  "5/4": "",
  "2/5": "",
  "3/5": "",
  "Using sin²x + cos²x = 1: (3/5)² + cos²x = 1, so cos²x = 1 - 9/25 = 16/25, and cos x = 4/5 (positive in Quadrant I).": "",
  "Which expression is equivalent to 1 + tan²x?": "",
  "cos²x": "",
  "cot²x": "",
  "csc²x": "",
  "sec²x": "",
