  "What is a trigonometric identity?": "",
  "A formula used only for right triangles": "",
  "An equation that is true for all values of the variable where both sides are defined": "",
  "An approximation used in trigonometric calculations": "",
  "An equation that is true for only specific values of the variable": "",
  "A trigonometric identity is an equation involving trigonometric functions that is true for all values of the variable in its domain. Unlike equations, identities hold universally.": "",
  "What does the term 'cofunction' mean in trigonometry?": "",
  "Two functions that are inverses of each other": "",
  "Two functions whose values are equal when their arguments sum to 90° (π/2)": "",
  "Two functions with the same period": "",
  "Two functions that always have the same value": "",
  "Cofunctions are pairs of trigonometric functions whose values are equal when their arguments are complementary (sum to 90°). For example, sin x = cos(90° - x).": "",
  "What is the definition of a reciprocal identity in trigonometry?": "",
  "An identity involving the sum of two angles": "",
  "An identity that expresses one trigonometric function as the reciprocal of another": "",
  "An identity relating a function to its negative": "",
  "An identity that uses the Pythagorean theorem": "",
  "A reciprocal identity expresses one trig function as 1 divided by another: csc x = 1/sin x, sec x = 1/cos x, and cot x = 1/tan x.": "",
  "What does it mean to 'verify' a trigonometric identity?": "",
  "To graph both sides and compare": "",
  "To show algebraically that one side of the equation can be transformed into the other": "",
  "To substitute a specific value to check if both sides are equal": "",
  "To solve the equation for x": "",
  "Verifying an identity means using algebraic manipulations and known identities to transform one side of the equation until it matches the other side, proving the equation holds for all valid values.": "",
  "What is the 'double-angle formula' in trigonometry?": "",
  "A formula that relates two different trigonometric functions": "",
  "A formula that expresses a trigonometric function of 2x in terms of functions of x": "",
  "A formula that doubles the value of a trigonometric function": "",
  "A formula that works only for angles in the second quadrant": "",
  "A double-angle formula expresses a trig function of twice an angle (2x) in terms of trig functions of x. For example, sin 2x = 2 sin x cos x.": "",
  "What is a 'half-angle formula' used for?": "",
  "To reduce the period of a trig function by half": "",
  "To divide an angle measurement by two": "",
  "To find the value of a trig function for half of a given angle using the full angle's trig values": "",
  "To calculate the area of a half-circle": "",
  "A half-angle formula lets you find sin(x/2), cos(x/2), or tan(x/2) using known values of sin x and cos x. For example, sin(x/2) = ±√((1 - cos x)/2).": "",
  "What does the term 'sum-to-product identity' refer to?": "",
  "An identity for multiplying sine and cosine values": "",
  "An identity that converts a sum or difference of trig functions into a product": "",
  "An identity that adds two trigonometric functions together": "",
  "An identity that converts a product of trig functions into a sum": "",
  "Sum-to-product identities convert sums or differences of sine/cosine into products. For example, sin A + sin B = 2 sin((A+B)/2) cos((A-B)/2).": "",
  "What is meant by an 'even function' in the context of trigonometric identities?": "",
  "A function that only takes even-numbered angle inputs": "",
  "A function that always produces positive outputs": "",
  "A function whose period is an even number": "",
  "A function whose graph is symmetric about the y-axis, where f(-x) = f(x)": "",
  "An even function satisfies f(-x) = f(x) and is symmetric about the y-axis. Cosine is an even function because cos(-x) = cos x.": "",
  "What does 'odd function' mean for a trigonometric function?": "",
  "A function with an odd-numbered period": "",
  "A function whose graph is symmetric about the origin, where f(-x) = -f(x)": "",
  "A function that is undefined at even multiples of π": "",
  "A function that only works for odd angles": "",
  "An odd function satisfies f(-x) = -f(x) and has origin symmetry. Sine and tangent are odd functions: sin(-x) = -sin x and tan(-x) = -tan x.": "",
  "What is a 'power-reducing formula' in trigonometry?": "",
  "A formula that lowers the degree of a polynomial": "",
  "A formula that reduces the value of a trig function": "",
  "A formula that simplifies exponents in algebraic expressions": "",
  "A formula that converts higher powers of trig functions into expressions with lower powers": "",
  "Power-reducing formulas express squared (or higher power) trig functions in terms of first-power trig functions of a multiple angle. For example, sin²x = (1 - cos 2x)/2.": "",
  "A sound engineer models a wave as y = sin²(x) + cos²(x). After applying the Pythagorean identity, what is the simplified output of the wave?": "",
  "y = 1": "",
  "y = 0": "",
  "y = 2": "",
  "y = sin 2x": "",
  "By the Pythagorean identity, sin²x + cos²x = 1 for all x. The simplified output is the constant y = 1.": "",
  "A physics student needs to find the exact value of sin 75° using the sum formula sin(45° + 30°). What is the result?": "",
  "(√6 + √2)/4": "",
  "(√3 + 1)/4": "",
  "(√6 - √2)/4": "",
  "(√2 + √3)/2": "",
  "sin 75° = sin(45° + 30°) = sin 45° cos 30° + cos 45° sin 30° = (√2/2)(√3/2) + (√2/2)(1/2) = (√6 + √2)/4.": "",
  "An electrical engineer is analyzing a circuit where the voltage is modeled by V = 2 sin x cos x. Using the double-angle formula, which simplified expression should the engineer use?": "",
  "V = sin 2x": "",
